ssion. This process may contribute to Neptune\'s excess heat.'},{name:'Atmosphere',pct:25,color:'#4488cc',label:'Hydrogen/helium/methane (H\u2082/He/CH\u2084 \u2014 80/19/1.5%)',desc:'~5,000 km atmosphere. Deeper blue than Uranus (possibly from an unknown chromophore). Most dynamic ice-giant atmosphere: 1,200+ mph supersonic winds, transient Great Dark Spots, bright methane cirrus clouds. Driven by internal heat, not solar energy.'}],note:'Neptune radiates 2.6\u00d7 more energy than it receives from the Sun, yet Uranus (nearly identical in size/composition) barely radiates any excess \u2014 one of planetary science\'s biggest mysteries. The similar offset, tilted magnetic fields of both planets point to a shared superionic-water dynamo mechanism.'},moon:{layers:[{name:'Solid inner core',pct:14,color:'#c0a080',label:'Iron (Fe)',desc:'Solid Fe inner core ~258 km radius (~14% of lunar radius). Confirmed as solid by Briaud et al. 2023 (Nature) using lunar laser ranging + GRAIL gravity. Temp ~2,400\u00b0F. Only ~1% of Moon\'s mass \u2014 the Moon is iron-depleted compared to Earth.'},{name:'Liquid outer core',pct:6,color:'#b09070',label:'Iron-sulfur (Fe-S)',desc:'Molten Fe-S outer core to ~362 km radius. Contains dissolved sulfur and carbon. Too small and cool today to sustain a dynamo \u2014 but the Moon DID have a magnetic field from ~4.2 to 3.6 Bya (recorded in Apollo rock samples, some stronger than Earth\'s today).'},{name:'Partial-melt layer',pct:8,color:'#8a7060',label:'Molten silicate rock',desc:'A ~150 km partially molten silicate layer at the core-mantle boundary, first inferred by Weber et al. 2011 from Apollo seismogram reanalysis and retained by subsequent models. Unique to the Moon \u2014 thermally insulates the core and explains persistence of the tiny liquid outer core today.'},{name:'Mantle',pct:69.7,color:'#a09080',label:'Silicate rock (olivine + pyroxene)',desc:'Single rigid silicate mantle, ~1,300 km thick. Magnesium-rich olivine and pyroxene. Source 